    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Inner Peace",
      "uuid": "243f3a99631c45f6a344c32c4c3580fb",
      "x": 4190.706433881296,
      "y": 2173.090353084497,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 3160.0,
      "z_value": -9.904000000000053,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC \"-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN\" \"http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd\">\n<html><head><meta name=\"qrichtext\" content=\"1\" /><meta charset=\"utf-8\" /><style type=\"text/css\">\np, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }\nhr { height: 1px; border-width: 0; }\nli.unchecked::marker { content: \"\\2610\"; }\nli.checked::marker { content: \"\\2612\"; }\n</style></head><body style=\" font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:9pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;\">\n<p style=\" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\">This is a poem</p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\">in a line</p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\">It's not a line pretending to be a poem</p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\">Other way around this time</p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\">But I still wrote it</p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;\">Just for you<br /><br /><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000099;\">One day John, the brother of James [these are the sons of Zebedee], was going up to the Temple. A Pharisee by the name of Arimanios came up to him and challenged him, asking: &quot;Where is the teacher you used to follow?&quot;</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; line-height:20px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000099;\">John replied, &quot;He has gone back to the place from which he came.&quot;</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; line-height:20px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000099;\">The Pharisee said, &quot;That Nazarene misled you (plural), told you lies, closed your hearts and turned you away from your ancestral traditions.\u201d</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; line-height:20px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000099;\">When I heard these things, I, John, turned away from the temple and went off to a deserted mountainous place. I was very unhappy, saying to myself:</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:40px; margin-right:40px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000099;\">&quot;How was the Savior designated?<br />Why did his Father send him into the world?<br />Who is his Father?<br />What kind of realm will we go to?</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; line-height:20px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000099;\">For, although he told us, \u2018This realm is modeled on the imperishable realm,\u2019<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 He didn't teach us about the latter.\u201d</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; line-height:20px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000099;\">All of a sudden, while I was contemplating these things,<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Behold!<br />The heavens opened and the whole of creation shone with a light from above,<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 And the world quaked!<br />I was afraid, yet<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Behold!</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; line-height:20px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000099;\">A little child appeared before me in the light.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 I continued looking at him as he became an old man<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 And then he changed again, becoming like a young man.<br />I didn't understand what I was seeing,<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 But the one likeness had several forms in the light,<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 And these likenesses appeared each through the other<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 And the vision had three forms.</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; line-height:20px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000099;\">He said to me,<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 \u201cJohn, why doubt?<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Why be afraid?<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Don\u2019t you know this image?<br />Be not afraid.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 I am with you (plural) always.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 I am the Father<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 The Mother<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 The Son<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 I am the incorruptible<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Purity.</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; line-height:20px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000099;\">I have come to teach you<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 About what is<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 And what was<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 And what will be<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 In order for you to understand<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 The invisible world<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 And the world that is visible<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 And the immovable race of perfect humanity.</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000099;\">Raise your head;<br />Understand my lessons;<br />Share them with any others who have received the spirit,<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Who are from the immovable race of perfect humanity.\u201d</span><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\"><br />\u00a0</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; line-height:20px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; font-weight:700; font-style:italic; color:#000000;\">The Inexpressible One</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">The One rules all. Nothing has authority over it.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 It is the God.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 It is Father of everything,<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Holy One<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 The invisible one over everything.<br />It is uncontaminated<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Pure light no eye can bear to look within.</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">The One is the Invisible Spirit.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 It is not right to think of it as a God or as like God.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 It is more than just God.</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">Nothing is above it.<br />Nothing rules it.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Since everything exists within it<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 It does not exist within anything.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Since it is not dependent on anything<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 It is eternal.</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">It is absolutely complete and so needs nothing.<br />It is utterly perfect<br />Light.</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">The One is without boundaries<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Nothing exists outside of it to border it<br />The One cannot be investigated<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Nothing exists apart from it to investigate it<br />The One cannot be measured<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Nothing exists external to it to measure it</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">The One cannot be seen<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 For no one can envision it<br />The One is eternal<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 For it exists forever<br />The One is inconceivable<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 For no one can comprehend it<br />The One is indescribable<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 For no one can put any words to it.</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">The One is infinite light<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Purity<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Holiness<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Stainless,</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">The One is incomprehensible<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Perfectly free from corruption.<br />Not \u201cperfect\u201d<br />Not \u201cblessed\u201d<br />Not \u201cdivine\u201d<br />But superior to such concepts.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Neither physical nor unphysical<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Neither immense nor infinitesimal<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 It is impossible to specify in quantity or quality<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 For it is beyond knowledge.</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">The One is not a being among other beings\u00a0<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 It is vastly superior<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 But it is not \u201csuperior.\u201d</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">It is outside of realms of being and time<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 For whatever is within realms of being was created<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 And whatever is within time had time allotted to it<br />The One receives nothing from anything.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 It simply apprehends itself in its own perfect light</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">The One is majestic.<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 The One is measureless majesty</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">Chief of all Realms<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Producing all realms</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">Light<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Producing light</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">Life<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Producing life</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">Blessedness<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Producing blessedness</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">Knowledge<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Producing knowledge</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">Good<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Producing goodness</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">Mercy<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Producing mercy</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">Generous<br />\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Producing generosity</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0[It does not \u201cpossess\u201d these things.]</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">It gives forth light beyond measure, beyond comprehension.</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">[What can I say?]</span></p>\n<p style=\" margin-top:12px; margin-bottom:12px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; background-color:#ffffff;\"><span style=\" font-family:'serif'; color:#000000;\">His realm is eternal, peaceful, silent, resting, before everything.<br />He is the head of every realm sustaining each of them through goodness.</span></p></body></html>"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "sticker",
      "title": "Sticker",
      "uuid": "a6e9dfa4934b424285a654cad68f3cf5",
      "x": 7160.386401921172,
      "y": 1166.8432998571734,
      "width": 400.0,
      "height": 400.0,
      "z_value": 100.0,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "pinned": false,
      "pin_vp_x": 0.0,
      "pin_vp_y": 0.0,
      "pin_scale": 1.0,
      "cache_key": "78074f927575afbe1f9f9997f08b90f894b57a56ee2bb36ef3cff25d520f9147.png",
      "source_path": "C:\\Users\\thisg\\Desktop\\Intricate\\icons\\directAudio.png",
      "source_size": 343447,
      "source_mtime": 1775828879.7338324,
      "image_b64": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "92d67d3627444409ab7c49fef98af1b8",
      "x": 19460.33282964087,
      "y": 10647.496983739007,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.831000000000094,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "If Rev 22:16 is the morning star + sent angel, and John's impulse is write-but-sometimes-seal, then the unknown quote reads almost like a response from the other side of the seal \u2014 someone speaking from inside the awakened community, promising the sealed material can be translated, and describing the entry condition as refusal of war."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "d7f0d82363f040448418a8e8d324736a",
      "x": 7993.880374961293,
      "y": 3940.2500770639945,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.89300000000006,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "It's part of Section 45's prophecy about Zion in the last days \u2014 Zion as a gathering place for the righteous from all nations, and the one community on earth not at war with itself. Section 45 is generally understood as the \"Second Coming\" revelation, given to Joseph Smith in spring 1831, and verses 66\u201371 specifically describe the establishment and character of the New Jerusalem. \nLDS Living"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Boundless Joy",
      "uuid": "244f2763a4184910a447129af4285294",
      "x": 4889.798975064794,
      "y": 1683.0103748294696,
      "width": 405.1847512792499,
      "height": 433.7589446820507,
      "z_value": -9.950000000000028,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"the entire first chapter is essentially \"and it was good, and it was good, and it was VERY good.\" Not exactly understated.\" lol, yes, also genesis 1:31 \"And he looked upon what he had made and it was great\" (slightly paraphrased), its one of my favorite verses in the entire book, just look at what we have made, its pretty great, I quote it all the time for fun. but check this... what does that verse actually mean beyond the apparent accomplishments and God having decided to start the concept of time at that point, when he felt confidence that the world was ready to be set into motion? he paused... and took status of his work... it means he also has doubt, if he didn't have the concept of doubt then why did he pause to check and not just one-shot it, start creation and go have coffee, no he paused and checked the status of it in genesis 1:31... he doesn't just have pride he also has doubt, the dude has all kinds of emotional spectrums, yet we are told he is infallible. why do you think that is? how can an infallible being be full of things like pride and doubt? not to mention his jealousy by starting the first commandment on \"hey don't be worshipping others, you just need me\" (slightly paraphrased as well of course, he said there is but one God)\nthink about it.. both statements hold true, he is basically a neurotic mess with all the emotional scales that we have, but is also infallible, how can these two statements both be true?\n\nIt's because he is everything, the concept of pure existence.  He wouldn't be infallable everything unless he posessed our flaws as well...."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "743425eebaee42ebbf44000eedf7309c",
      "x": 22409.608178298,
      "y": 13193.481451136626,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.810000000000105,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The translation promise becomes interesting. If the quote predates the canonical texts, then \"I will ensure you can translate all of this\" isn't about translating a sealed scripture \u2014 it's about the promise that what is being said now will remain transmissible. That's a much older concern. It's the concern of every oral tradition crossing into writing, and every esoteric tradition crossing language boundaries. The Hermetic corpus has this energy. So do certain Vedic transmission lineages."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "eb0509fe46024c2b9071e1831203b38f",
      "x": 32795.26103709036,
      "y": 21097.008109376206,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.727000000000151,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"There will be a gathering of all humans, but only those who do not partake in war\" \u2014 This is where it gets interesting. The Hermetic corpus is not a pacifist tradition in the Buddhist sense, but it is anti-passion, and war is the paradigmatic expression of the lower passions binding the soul to matter. Poimandres lists the qualities cast off in ascent: deceit, desire, arrogance, audacity, evil striving, greed, falsehood. The warring impulse \u2014 the thumos in Platonic terms \u2014 is one of the planetary garments shed in the return. So the Hermetic awakened are not those who refused war as a precept, but those who transcended the passion that produces war. Same outcome, different metaphysics."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "bc8ddb5b468f4ee3a7fcaf30dc6d38b1",
      "x": 28568.960927625925,
      "y": 16345.645751935574,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.762000000000132,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That reading also rhymes with how the fig tree functions in D&C 45:36\u201338 and the Synoptics. The fig tree isn't really a story \u2014 it's a demonstration. \"Look at the tree. The leaves are out. You know summer is near.\" It's parable-as-pointer, parable-as-direct-showing, not parable-as-allegory. Same with the burning house in the Lotus Sutra \u2014 it's a configuration that shows, not a tale that tells."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Kinetic",
      "uuid": "4cce0e0fd49c449385531e8ad8d5668d",
      "x": 3587.4198429009084,
      "y": 2314.787880056894,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.926000000000041,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "And confirm his plan did indeed work quite fine by adding into this the context of Genesis 3:22\n\nAnd the lord God said \n\"look! The man who now become like one of us\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b50ea104424e4ca39c74a29f0818219d",
      "x": 17469.415171775163,
      "y": 10767.970160671282,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.83800000000009,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "John's impulse \u2014 across Revelation 1:11, 1:19, 10:4, 22:10 \u2014 is the repeated command to write, with one striking exception at 10:4 where John is told to seal up what the seven thunders said and not write it. So John's impulse is bidirectional: write everything, except what's sealed."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "38fd0b20959b48acaa89ceafd66f8e50",
      "x": 27025.291294926286,
      "y": 14703.441818901063,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.769000000000128,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "So if your unknown quote rattles against Krishna, it rattles by contrast more than by resonance. The Buddhist substrate fits better. But Krishna gives you something the Buddhist frame doesn't: the theophanic register for \"light arrives,\" which is closer to Revelation 1:7's \"every eye shall see him\" than anything in the Pali Canon."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Proverbs 13:20",
      "uuid": "be4a4625eb4c43dda56b47e373f80eae",
      "x": 5212.53520827512,
      "y": 3200.909107941954,
      "width": 280.32220504033876,
      "height": 117.27306738623466,
      "z_value": -9.698000000000167,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Walk with the wise and become wise, for a companion of fools suffers harm."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "5d8f55c5fc6e4db5a68a9b9cadd7d573",
      "x": 14147.338570268821,
      "y": 5417.320494978692,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.865000000000075,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The poetic compression is nice, but it collapses the sequence (signs \u2192 resurrection \u2192 gathering \u2192 Zion) into something more simultaneous, and it shifts Zion from refuge-for-the-peaceful into something closer to a filtered community."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "efc3b80c510f42909c4a86b2fa5f5028",
      "x": 14912.326717261869,
      "y": 9609.53170240839,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.850000000000083,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"Only those who do not partake in war\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "59a5711a8a7c42b6a8e071426507fe08",
      "x": 8731.105360479603,
      "y": 5441.0124368469005,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.890000000000061,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Fetched: Doctrine and Covenants 45\nFetched: Doctrine and Covenants 45\nVerse 61 reads:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "80e034b747bd4a46ab28ee6f27614e8e",
      "x": 15276.779948914376,
      "y": 9703.192923792774,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.849000000000084,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is the sharpest diff and the most theologically loaded part of your phrasing. Revelation has no pacifism filter for entry. Quite the opposite \u2014 Revelation 19 has Christ riding a white horse, robe dipped in blood, and the saints follow as armies. Revelation 12:11 has the saints overcoming \"by the blood of the Lamb, and by the word of their testimony\" \u2014 testimony is the weapon, but the framing is martial. Revelation 21:8 names cowards first in the list of those excluded from the New Jerusalem. So Revelation does not gate entry on non-violence; it gates on faithfulness, often under violence."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "acc327deafcc4bf39327ad595cbbc7ec",
      "x": 9143.80965487815,
      "y": 5350.333584354139,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.889000000000062,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"Wherefore I give unto you that ye may now translate it, that ye may be prepared for the things to come.\" \nThe Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "8bf65a4873224518ab9944e91a2e13fb",
      "x": 21167.589475801124,
      "y": 10429.83328696626,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.825000000000097,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The phenomenon you're describing has a name in textual studies \u2014 intertextual resonance without dependence. A text can sit in the same conceptual gravity well as canonical sources, using the same imaginal vocabulary (light, parable, trumpet/song, awakening, translation, gathering, peace), without being downstream of any of them in a citation sense. It's \"in the water\" of a tradition rather than drawn from a specific well."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "7e85b93bde8a43dcb21e5dd3f1a99090",
      "x": 18627.31301325619,
      "y": 10400.61998300273,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.834000000000092,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"I will ensure you can translate all of this\" \u2014 set against John's impulse, this is the inverse promise. John is told to write (and sometimes seal). The quote's speaker promises translatability \u2014 that the recorded thing will be made readable. That's a post-canonical concern. It only makes sense in a tradition that already has a sealed text and is worried about access to it. D&C 45:61 fits that perfectly (1831, translating the NT). Revelation does not \u2014 Revelation assumes its recipient is the writer, not a later translator."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3255f6e9df00418191a10dcdf49dc14e",
      "x": 15198.737642884244,
      "y": 8978.828016275967,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.853000000000081,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is the cleanest diff. D&C 45:60\u201361 is institutionally specific: translate the New Testament so you can understand. Revelation's parallel impulse is John being told to write (Revelation 1:11, 1:19, 22:10 \u2014 \"seal not the sayings of the prophecy of this book\"). The verb is different \u2014 write/transmit, not translate \u2014 and the recipient is not promised translation capacity but rather commanded to record. Genesis's analog is Genesis 5:1 (\"the book of the generations of Adam\") and the broader patriarchal pattern of covenant-as-recorded-promise (Genesis 15, 17). So your phrasing is uniquely D&C; nothing in either Revelation or Genesis frames the conveyor of prophecy as receiving translation help."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "image",
      "title": "Image",
      "uuid": "1e62be7513754c8887a375681e22f575",
      "x": 2965.1314502786154,
      "y": -376.8659820535486,
      "width": 422.90694948870214,
      "height": 899.2555609731764,
      "z_value": -9.990000000000006,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "image_b64": "",
      "cache_key": "5bb1041b6d196adc89fda0a34fb182f8c6d9b0f105a7c1e7896487fa1e68ef04",
      "caption": "Lectures On Faith book cover",
      "source_path": "C:\\Users\\thisg\\Desktop\\Lectures On Faith\\Pages\\Lectures on Faith.png",
      "source_size": 26888,
      "source_mtime": 1774982071.149399,
      "show_border": true,
      "depth_front": false
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "20d0b913c94f4c988551532cea67690c",
      "x": 13106.09753114411,
      "y": 5591.063297201314,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.869000000000073,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Light breaking forth \u2192 parable as sign (v.36\u201338) \u2713\nTranslation instruction (v.60\u201361) \u2713\nGathering from every nation (v.69) \u2713\nConnection between non-war and Zion (v.68\u201369) \u2713\nWhere your version drifts from the text:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "68260707b33e47fe80ad8615725881eb",
      "x": 9627.40123995909,
      "y": 4952.639957711608,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.883000000000065,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: 45:36.\n45:36. Probably also then"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b9f7b066f37942a98be8e217109c0361",
      "x": 23500.40000432498,
      "y": 13720.268067827752,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.788000000000117,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That's a meaningful diff from your unknown quote. The quote softens the revelation through parable. Krishna doesn't."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "4b80d45a9e5543de905dfb0a838101e4",
      "x": 28128.17958644502,
      "y": 16433.639422386877,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.763000000000131,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"With this parable I will show you\" can mean: the parable is the showing. Not a story that points at the truth, but a configuration through which the truth is directly disclosed. That's much closer to Krishna's vishvarupa than I gave it credit for. The vision Arjuna receives in chapter 11 is a kind of parable in the older sense \u2014 parabol\u0113, a placing-alongside, a configuration that lets you see. It's not narrative pedagogy; it's structured unveiling."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3826fb489c554bc8b8113390feff35e0",
      "x": 16677.505665660585,
      "y": 10783.505670203942,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.841000000000088,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: Fair \u2014 I'll re-tag it as unknown-author quote rather than your phrasing.\nFair \u2014 I'll re-tag it as unknown-author quote rather than your phrasing. That actually changes the analysis a bit, because if we're treating it as a found text, the question shifts from \"where did you drift from D&C 45\" to \"where does this quote sit in the broader scriptural ecology.\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1908878bb9d441cebdae091aca92b2cc",
      "x": 25528.987073419496,
      "y": 13391.422097929817,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.777000000000124,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is the sharpest divergence and the most theologically loaded. Krishna's central teaching to Arjuna is fight. The entire Gita is a battlefield discourse arguing Arjuna into combat. Gita 2:31\u201333: as a kshatriya, Arjuna's dharma is righteous war, and refusing it would be sin. Gita 2:38: fight without attachment to victory or defeat. The whole text reframes violence as compatible with \u2014 even required by \u2014 spiritual realization, when performed without ego-attachment to outcomes."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "294d07a7ddde4643b5173f817a9f823f",
      "x": 15860.13285680518,
      "y": 10986.808365204297,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.845000000000086,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Your phrasing is closer to a Millennial Zion theology \u2014 the peaceable kingdom of Isaiah 2:4 / Micah 4:3 (\"they shall beat their swords into plowshares\u2026 neither shall they learn war any more\"). That's Old Testament prophetic, not Revelation, and not Genesis. D&C 45 is drawing on that Isaianic stream, which is why your paraphrase felt natural."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "fe7750f9ca55464781bac5c34ad316ff",
      "x": 15990.515693925106,
      "y": 10498.847205583092,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.843000000000087,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: The revelation 22:16 part is the thought that lingers, compounded with John's impulse.\nThe revelation 22:16 part is the thought that lingers, compounded with John's impulse."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "244e69f9ce51407ebd66dbaf5abb6a2f",
      "x": 24899.35317936577,
      "y": 13695.479619454867,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.78400000000012,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "On translation and transmission:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "d75fcbbea80c49398fe127732eeb896a",
      "x": 29758.742471125403,
      "y": 18992.37948726632,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.751000000000138,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That maps onto the vishvarupa almost exactly. Arjuna doesn't receive a teaching about the universal form; he receives the seeing of it, and the seeing is what undoes him. He begs Krishna to stop showing. The spectacle is too much. That's not pedagogy \u2014 it's ontological exposure."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "7cbb4268d2424d1ebe266a77f8778894",
      "x": 15463.781795670624,
      "y": 10956.98862565153,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.846000000000085,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Where your version actually lands"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "80b88675bfa34961ac301f2e012aafaa",
      "x": 9573.832412199026,
      "y": 5550.978209039766,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.885000000000064,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"But before the arm of the Lord shall fall, an angel shall sound his trump, and the saints that have slept shall come forth to meet me in the cloud.\" \nThe Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "2e20b533bd1c42348af89b665e3c9d29",
      "x": 24185.11737061883,
      "y": 13319.392870222318,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.795000000000114,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The strongest tell: the combination of awakening-language, pacifism-as-entry, parabolic teaching, universal gathering, and a first-person-plural awakened voice is unusual. Each element shows up in other traditions, but the cluster is characteristic of Buddhist sangha framing in a way it isn't characteristic of, say, Jain or Pythagorean communities (which share some elements but not the parabolic teaching emphasis or the awakening-as-central-event frame)."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "God Himself",
      "uuid": "3de62dedae4246ef84c4e33f1ae14f67",
      "x": 2887.2480619107046,
      "y": 3846.801078366012,
      "width": 365.5504104501164,
      "height": 310.49752773690943,
      "z_value": 10.0,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Our faith in him, and the holy spirit which encumbers.\n\nThere are two sides of this tale that we can never tell \nWithout considering the other, \nThis immaculate bond \nBetween those who pursue answers \nAnd those who possess them,\nBoth must be discussed in equal value.\n\nThose are in effect the same, one being \nThe manifestation of the concept of God, \n\nGlory, Kindness, and Truth, \n\nWhile the counterpart being the human manifestation of such\n"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "4d8d1c0689634484b1d20b4552884ed5",
      "x": 35580.283714340636,
      "y": 21617.921364455724,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.718000000000156,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The Egyptian texts also have something the others don't quite have: the justified dead speaking in first person plural from the other side. The Book of the Dead has the deceased addressing the gods, sometimes with the chorus of the blessed responding. The \"we are awake\" voice has a real home there."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "30a840e8aba0427c8012dd026d6d5c73",
      "x": 36088.59884723564,
      "y": 21059.73911573583,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.71200000000016,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: Its worth noting, and thanks for the good talk, how this single statement flows through all of them and stops by each place like a casual friend among a group \u2026\nIts worth noting, and thanks for the good talk, how this single statement flows through all of them and stops by each place like a casual friend among a group agreeing on base premises but all differ slightly."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "8df7fcd94c1340a2a9589645184fa5d3",
      "x": 35732.64034993657,
      "y": 21090.83289013287,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.713000000000159,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "If that's the rattle \u2014 if the quote feels like it carries eros toward origin rather than fear of judgment or cessation of craving or covenant fidelity \u2014 then the Hermetic neighborhood is doing real work, and the \"older than all three\" feeling makes sense. You'd be hearing a thread that the canonical Abrahamic texts partially absorbed (especially through Hellenistic Judaism and Christian Platonism) but never made central."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "a4a99d2fb5b941bc8b1ea3cef32b7148",
      "x": 35221.186285897435,
      "y": 21571.217044639474,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.719000000000156,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "If your unknown quote draws on something genuinely old in this stream, you'd be looking at material that predates Genesis-as-text and predates the Buddha and predates the Upanishads' final form. Egyptian funerary and theological literature is one of the few candidate substrates that's that old and contains the full cluster: light-spectacle, awakening-as-recollection, collective ascended chorus, transmission-promise, transcendence-of-passion, universal gathering of those-who-knew."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "45bcf4132a0a49d2ab560df20b196a16",
      "x": 9989.801004154066,
      "y": 4780.293926264721,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.882000000000065,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: Verse 36:\nVerse 36:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "9b04830e15654538bbe9bd1fa01d260d",
      "x": 16223.082939531178,
      "y": 10737.31538096041,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.842000000000088,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"your phrasing leans Synoptic\"\n  Its not necessarily my phrasing, for now let's leave it tagged as a quote from unknown author."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "c4459427828a492aa9c4ce09f5a0b9ea",
      "x": 23388.844494253328,
      "y": 13469.744145799572,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.789000000000117,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Krishna's mode in the Bhagavad Gita is dialogic-revelatory, not parabolic in the Buddhist sense. He explains directly, then in chapter 11 does something neither Buddhism nor Abrahamic apocalypse quite does \u2014 he shows. The vishvarupa darshana, the vision of the universal form, is light-arrival as direct theophany: \"If the splendor of a thousand suns were to blaze forth all at once in the sky, that would be the splendor of that mighty Being\" (Gita 11:12). Arjuna sees and is undone. So the \"light arrives\" beat is there with overwhelming force, but the \"I will show you with this parable\" beat is replaced by direct vision. Krishna doesn't mediate through story when the moment comes; he unveils."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3299186a7a8447b2847308f9c3943baf",
      "x": 9005.002072669453,
      "y": 5940.3995194405925,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.887000000000063,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: Perhaps 45:45 as well?\nPerhaps 45:45 as well?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "6d39dac773c84a689de0b06d24c1ce81",
      "x": 36034.61114261305,
      "y": 20445.501258714612,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.705000000000163,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Thank you for the conversation. Holding a single statement up against five or six traditions and watching it visit each one without settling \u2014 that's a real way to think, and rarer than it should be. The fact that you're letting it remain unresolved is the thing. Most people would have flattened it into one tradition by now to stop the rattle. You're letting the rattle teach."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "4c320942062b458a8b1d1892898e9d1f",
      "x": 10986.879635328383,
      "y": 5294.9548653027505,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.879000000000067,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: As the light arrives I will show you with this parable, from there when you hear the angels sing you will know we are awake.\nAs the light arrives I will show you with this parable, from there when you hear the angels sing you will know we are awake. And I will ensure you can translate all of this.  There will be a gathering of all humans, but only those who do not partake in war"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ecc051224dda416bbb96bee3dbf9664d",
      "x": 16209.439576934023,
      "y": 10986.456414905644,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.844000000000086,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "One-line diff: Revelation gathers nations through judgment and worship; Genesis blesses nations through covenant lineage; D&C 45 gathers nations into Zion-as-refuge; your phrasing gathers nations through a pacifism filter \u2014 which is closest to Isaiah/Micah but not actually present in any of the three texts you're triangulating."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "107965faf59641f29446c2557be97853",
      "x": 18239.291025668088,
      "y": 10529.094881033348,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.835000000000091,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"when you hear the angels sing you will know we are awake\" \u2014 Rev 22:16 has Jesus sending his angel to testify, singular, declarative. The quote pluralizes it into singing angels and shifts the function from testimony to confirmation-of-waking. The \"we are awake\" is the most distinctive phrase in the whole quote \u2014 it's first-person plural, which neither Revelation nor D&C 45 uses for the resurrected. D&C 45:45 has \"the saints that have slept shall come forth\" (third person). Revelation 20:4 has the martyrs \"lived and reigned with Christ\" (third person). The \"we\" implies the speaker is among the waking \u2014 which is a perspective neither John nor Joseph occupies in their respective texts. The speaker in canonical apocalypse is always the witness, never the resurrected."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1c99412b26db46bbb5f1d019a27ada4b",
      "x": 21746.231395653445,
      "y": 11992.824064777129,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.8180000000001,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The lingering is the right response. Not every resonance needs to be flattened into a source."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "0550074bb0984fe3afc6a5e6ef467df9",
      "x": 20426.98509787238,
      "y": 10916.763374556742,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.829000000000095,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Possible homes for it: Quaker or Anabaptist devotional writing (the pacifism filter is a tell), a 19th-century millennialist tract (the \"we are awake\" + translation language fits), or a modern paraphrase from a peace-church tradition. The phrasing has the cadence of something translated from another language, or paraphrased loosely from a longer original \u2014 the rhythm is too clean to be extemporaneous but too unspecific to be canonical."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "dfa06308e2ac4f468edaadcab1442967",
      "x": 14864.619579372946,
      "y": 6881.93677423382,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.862000000000076,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Searched the web\nSearched the web\nGood \u2014 I have enough to do this comparison properly. Let me also check Genesis on the relevant gathering/peace/covenant motifs since you wanted that diff specifically."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "image",
      "title": "Image",
      "uuid": "99421cf7078f401cac9965abc973c402",
      "x": 2237.0668142870127,
      "y": 2277.478329703865,
      "width": 328.1743801254057,
      "height": 685.482841501459,
      "z_value": -9.984000000000009,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "image_b64": "",
      "cache_key": "b74ed4dffad8f988b9eb44d29debdfdfb5887e3c18406658cd413761e2ded962",
      "caption": "Religious theological discussion on humanity",
      "source_path": "C:\\Users\\thisg\\Desktop\\Lectures On Faith\\Pages\\Lectures on Faith2.png",
      "source_size": 383799,
      "source_mtime": 1774983490.9731534,
      "show_border": true,
      "depth_front": false
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b21fb6e00551414a9218dbdb8f5261e9",
      "x": 9360.03429034536,
      "y": 5905.597152383421,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.886000000000063,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: Verse 45:\nVerse 45:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "668049682e244b028243476db5dfd32c",
      "x": 21673.736571839767,
      "y": 11114.914540281714,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.823000000000098,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Shared substrate. All three of your reference points (Genesis, Revelation, D&C 45) draw on older Hebrew prophetic vocabulary \u2014 Isaiah, Joel, Zechariah, Daniel. A fourth text drinking from the same prophetic stream will rhyme with all three without being descended from any of them. It's why Sufi poetry and Christian mysticism sometimes feel uncannily parallel \u2014 they're independently engaging the same set of perennial images."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "The Man",
      "uuid": "7db8e7a2abaa42228bde0fdaee1d8eb2",
      "x": 2804.948957101282,
      "y": 3038.30605965468,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 712.0,
      "z_value": -9.939000000000034,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "We have previously covered the characters, the events, the prophecies, the how, the what, the why, and the where.\n\nWe shift our focus here slightly, and discuss the actual topic at hand, God himself, our faith in him, and the holy spirit which encumbers.\n\nThere are two sides of this tale that we can never tell without the other, this immaculate bond between those who pursue these answers and those who posess them, so both must be discussed in equal value.\n\nThese are in effect the same, one being the manifestation of the concept of God, Glory, Kindness, and Truth, while the counterpart being the human manifestation of such\n\nIt's relatively simple to start this talk on nothing other than referring to Genesis 1:26\n\nThen God said\n\"Let us make mankind in our image,\nIn our likeness, so that they may rule\nOver the fish in the sea and the birds\nIn the sky, over the livestock and all\nThe wild animals, and over all the creatures\nThat move along the ground\"\n\nSo that we are all on the same page regarding the purpose of the original design, that you are a heavenly creature.\n\nAnd confirm that his plan indeed did work fine by adding into this context Genesis 3:22\n\nAnd the lord God said\n\"The man has now become like one of us\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "f17e9574d33a45048f73c9a5828a91b8",
      "x": 21486.37041564831,
      "y": 11379.652940146954,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.822000000000099,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The \"almost-quote\" effect. When language is rhythmically scriptural \u2014 parallelism, conditional clauses, the and\u2026 and\u2026 and cadence \u2014 the brain pattern-matches it as familiar even when no specific verse is its source. Cormac McCarthy does this deliberately; so do a lot of devotional writers. The quote you have has that cadence, which is part of why it rattles."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "That phrase tightens it considerably",
      "uuid": "cf22fcc47f9643ef9787f685903cce58",
      "x": 29688.79640840925,
      "y": 18160.754875741986,
      "width": 389.0625,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.701000000000166,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "That phrase tightens it considerably",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "8028133e928e48cea26b830b73539ea6",
      "x": 31614.82375412827,
      "y": 20160.642487836216,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.734000000000147,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Genesis: soul is created by divine breath into formed dust (Gen 2:7). Origin is creational, not pre-existent.\nRevelation: souls are creaturely, redeemed through Christ, awaiting resurrection. No pre-existence claim.\nD&C 45: actually closer to Hermetic on this \u2014 Joseph Smith's later theology does posit pre-existent intelligences (D&C 93:29: \"intelligence... was not created or made, neither indeed can be\"), but D&C 45 itself doesn't develop this.\nBuddhist sangha: explicitly rejects an atman (permanent soul). Awakening is cessation, not return.\nKrishna/Gita: soul (atman) is eternal and uncreated (Gita 2:20), but not \"divine\" in the Hermetic sense \u2014 it's a fragment of Brahman, not a fallen luminous being.\nUpanishads: closest of the Indic strands to Hermetic. Tat tvam asi \u2014 \"thou art that.\" The atman is Brahman, and ignorance of this is the bondage.\nThe Hermetic frame and the Upanishadic frame are siblings here, possibly even cousins through historical contact (there's serious scholarship on Indian-Hellenistic philosophical exchange via Alexandria). Both say: the soul is divine in origin, has forgotten itself, and awakens by remembering."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "9f360f374f4243fdbaa239ad3c2e0045",
      "x": 25316.323513254098,
      "y": 13624.59906465059,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.78200000000012,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is the closest Krishna gets to your quote's \"I will ensure you can translate all of this.\" But notice the difference: Krishna's claim is recovery, not translatability. The teaching was lost and is being restored to Arjuna. There's no promise that it will be translatable forward \u2014 only that it has been transmitted now. That's a cyclical concern (yugas, ages, recurring loss and recovery), not a linear-eschatological concern (sealed text, future translator)."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "55fd8187705b40f282fe7c8bb8e373a6",
      "x": 23856.29967850669,
      "y": 13844.966637854088,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.797000000000113,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"Angels sing\" \u2014 Buddhism doesn't have angels in the Abrahamic sense, but it does have devas (celestial beings) who sing and rain flowers at moments of awakening. The Lotus Sutra opens with devas making music. So \"angels sing\" might be an Abrahamic-language rendering of a deva scene. That actually fits the \"translated across tradition boundary\" feeling I mentioned earlier."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "2a61a72b50f646deaf01b38692ab18aa",
      "x": 23659.213142390985,
      "y": 14181.206767693848,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.799000000000111,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Where it fits less cleanly:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "a912afcce0444602b82b4fbb0d75fa12",
      "x": 19448.1516865001,
      "y": 10937.259460240615,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.830000000000094,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That's not any one canonical voice. It reads more like a reception text \u2014 something written by a community that has already received Revelation and is articulating what it would feel like to be on the fulfillment side of John's vision."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3131fae4567e44928fa0482b82f68408",
      "x": 11391.634439046466,
      "y": 5219.093453874535,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.877000000000068,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The \"parable\" in v.36 is specifically the fig tree (v.37\u201338) \u2014 leaves coming out signals summer is near, i.e. the signs are the cue that Christ's coming is close.\nThe angel's trump in v.45 isn't quite \"angels singing\" \u2014 it's a single trumpet blast that wakes the sleeping saints (the resurrection moment) right before judgment falls.\nv.61 is narrower than \"translate all of this\" \u2014 it's specifically the instruction to Joseph Smith to translate the New Testament so further understanding can come.\nv.69 is close to your reading: gathering from every nation, and Zion is the only people not at war among themselves. Worth noting it's \"not at war one with another\" \u2014 internal peace within Zion, rather than a pacifism test for entry. v.68 is the one closer to your \"those who do not partake in war\" idea: anyone unwilling to take up the sword against their neighbor flees to Zion for safety.\nSo a tighter paraphrase might be: When the light breaks forth, the fig tree parable is your sign. A trumpet will wake the sleeping saints to meet Christ. Translate the New Testament now to be ready. Zion will gather people from every nation \u2014 a refuge for those who refuse to war, and the one people not at war with itself."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "video",
      "title": "Video",
      "uuid": "27531301e1e642f7b6538fb425498390",
      "x": 4718.396635823152,
      "y": 704.0549445553825,
      "width": 822.2490403815616,
      "height": 837.2490403815616,
      "z_value": -9.932000000000038,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "source_path": "C:\\Users\\thisg\\Desktop\\_asset\\Clippy,Blessed be his name\\Counterparts.mp4",
      "cache_key": "fe5d9e636dd59f1338ce21efff9f7083ba043675b531e514cfdf4e0a28e7319b.mp4",
      "source_size": 3521339,
      "source_mtime": 1770654895.8541267,
      "caption": "Counterparts",
      "volume": 69,
      "playback_pos": 0,
      "looping": true,
      "muted": false,
      "show_border": true,
      "was_playing": false,
      "cache_enabled": true
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "4d4e96e488ae417e9f14a76bbe0d241a",
      "x": 22400.11041386348,
      "y": 12737.826431032334,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.811000000000105,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The pacifism filter reads differently. In the Abrahamic stream, non-violence as an entry condition is a late development (peace-church traditions, mostly post-Reformation). But in older traditions, refusal of violence as a marker of the awakened community shows up much earlier \u2014 Jain ahimsa, certain Buddhist sangha framings, some pre-Socratic Pythagorean communities, the Essene fragments. If your quote is older, the pacifism element stops being theologically anomalous and starts being characteristic."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "2c3363275f5e40d7941864a7411ff46f",
      "x": 21384.517968928103,
      "y": 11857.691562611517,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.8190000000001,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The fact that you're choosing not to cite \u2014 and that doing so would complicate the context \u2014 actually tells me something useful about where it likely sits: probably a tradition with a complicated relationship to the three you triangulated against, where naming the source would force a frame you'd rather leave open. That's a respectable choice, and a thing worth holding lightly rather than resolving."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "8f5f144f448e43ab9ffae19f653fb457",
      "x": 8932.138869604092,
      "y": 5110.607730598964,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.89100000000006,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: Verse 61 reads:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ad7f002b71b549f180a283b1f8b9e59b",
      "x": 23680.226772509657,
      "y": 14592.420651215367,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.80100000000011,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"Gathering of all humans\" \u2014 the sangha is in principle universal. The Buddha's teaching crosses caste, which was radical in 5th-century BCE India. Gathering \"from every nation under heaven\" maps reasonably onto the universalist claim of the dharma."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1c167629964a4a38a5ff24adbeea3225",
      "x": 23309.744166902117,
      "y": 14196.47271871874,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.80300000000011,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"When you hear the angels sing you will know we are awake\" \u2014 this is the strongest match. Buddha literally means \"the awakened one,\" and awakening (bodhi) is the central event, not resurrection. The first-person plural \"we are awake\" fits a sangha framing in a way it doesn't fit Abrahamic apocalyptic \u2014 the awakened community speaks from inside the awakening. In Mahayana especially, the bodhisattva sangha speaks collectively from the threshold of awakening. That's not a metaphor stretched; it's the literal frame."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "a444c6e244a144e7b4f3c36896f8f888",
      "x": 23323.328311246023,
      "y": 14622.069780665586,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.80200000000011,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"Only those who do not partake in war\" \u2014 ahimsa (non-harming) is the first of the five precepts (pa\u00f1cas\u012bla) binding on lay and monastic Buddhists alike. Refusing to take life is constitutive of sangha membership, not an aspirational add-on. So the pacifism filter, which I noted was anomalous in Revelation and narrower than D&C 45, is exactly characteristic of sangha boundaries."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "image",
      "title": "Image",
      "uuid": "8b3fa5b3708d4c188db81951c5218674",
      "x": 5637.119991466479,
      "y": 960.5520561655376,
      "width": 754.9336749719049,
      "height": 767.5979154693332,
      "z_value": -9.998000000000001,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "image_b64": "",
      "cache_key": "3c5f63d4eb1046dee147620a1c6ab4a6b4dc4fc7ef1cfebfc6b06aa5892b45cf",
      "caption": "Elegant woman skyline cityscape",
      "source_path": "C:\\Users\\thisg\\Desktop\\Lectures On Faith\\Images\\Counterpart.png",
      "source_size": 1102834,
      "source_mtime": 1774981577.1571143,
      "show_border": true,
      "depth_front": false
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "07ae424c11cd4e6bbf06b000abc5e58b",
      "x": 24052.631854190706,
      "y": 14421.241566968072,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.80000000000011,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"As the light arrives I will show you with this parable\" \u2014 the Buddha's pedagogy is overwhelmingly parabolic. The Lotus Sutra is essentially a sequence of parables (the burning house, the prodigal son, the magic city, the hidden jewel). \"Light arrives, I show you with parable\" is a fair description of how the dharma is transmitted. And light imagery \u2014 the Buddha as illuminator, dharma as lamp (\"be a lamp unto yourselves,\" Mahaparinibbana Sutta) \u2014 is pervasive."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ea55ef0d2dcf424aaed92b70ccac6bad",
      "x": 23386.049156012417,
      "y": 13176.933927798758,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.790000000000116,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "On light arriving and parable:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b32bcf8ecd96472ba4c18883f88c6a5f",
      "x": 24508.18024058032,
      "y": 14110.739210861868,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.786000000000119,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is where Krishna diverges most sharply from both the Buddhist and Abrahamic frames. Krishna's framing isn't \"the sleepers will wake\" \u2014 it's \"what looks like waking and sleeping is itself maya.\" Gita 2:69: \"What is night for all beings is the time of waking for the disciplined soul; and what is the time of waking for all beings is night for the sage who sees.\" Awakening in Krishna's mouth is inversion, not eschatological event. The disciplined are already awake while the world sleeps; there is no future trumpet because the trumpet is metaphysical, not temporal."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ba8954dfbbf74b31b3b00547edf71bdc",
      "x": 23748.715949315443,
      "y": 13138.603714460869,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.792000000000115,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: And which thoughts did Krishna have on this?\nAnd which thoughts did Krishna have on this?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "d431c3d090ad48c6a0fb733e8d226b31",
      "x": 23432.9285889676,
      "y": 12804.577692273857,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.791000000000116,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: Good move \u2014 Krishna's voice in the Gita is worth holding next to this, because it triangulates differently than Buddhist sangha does.\nGood move \u2014 Krishna's voice in the Gita is worth holding next to this, because it triangulates differently than Buddhist sangha does. Same neighborhood, different house."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "0b7312dbf11c4b2a8042d4dc6d555222",
      "x": 23784.563884741936,
      "y": 12885.488659117544,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.793000000000115,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Does that fit the shape of what's been rattling, or does it slide off in a particular spot?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "cd6875c68a324bceb409d55713175392",
      "x": 27444.060384077075,
      "y": 14817.207435005615,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.770000000000127,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Krishna shares the light beat (intensified into theophany), shares the transmission concern (as recovery rather than translation), shares the universal gathering (delocalized through bhakti), and opposes the pacifism beat. The \"we are awake\" beat doesn't translate well at all \u2014 Krishna's awakening is individual-perceptual, not collective-eschatological."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ab8a4e61bb8f4ee2a1ff65d553182a58",
      "x": 32288.237286478903,
      "y": 20982.532390963002,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.73000000000015,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"When you hear the angels sing you will know we are awake\" \u2014 The Hermetic ascent through the spheres is accompanied by the soul casting off the qualities given by each planetary ruler, and at the eighth sphere (the ogdoad) the soul joins the powers there in praising the Father. Poimandres I.26: at that point, the ascending soul \"hears certain powers above the ogdoadic nature, hymning God with a sweet voice.\" The awakened sing. And the soul joins them. \"We are awake\" \u2014 first-person plural \u2014 fits this exactly. The awakened community in Hermetic terms is the chorus of the ogdoad, the souls who have ascended and joined the singing."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "504c4e3389b146e892f6303539bc1fff",
      "x": 32141.0146410828,
      "y": 21217.288903461726,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.731000000000149,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That's a much stronger reading of \"I will show you with this parable\" than the Buddhist or Krishna readings. The Hermetic parable is the soul shown its own face."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "A series of faith affirmation lectures",
      "uuid": "346b0b18d45e4c18bfcc008f96754abf",
      "x": 2342.5959799854936,
      "y": 474.3440867806821,
      "width": 463.0180177897635,
      "height": 370.123749506879,
      "z_value": -9.703000000000165,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That have been in circulation for quite some time, written by Yours Truly.\n\nAs we started discussing some of the points from these private lectures, I began receiving more and more questions.\n\nAll these Intricate projects, they are all quite different each.\nThe events, the prophecies, the how, the what, the why.\nAnd the where.\n\nI felt inclined to show you around, like how I show a friend a hallway in our Arena, and you can experience it while it grows.\n\nThis one is a lecture series, and it starts like this.\n\nThe flowers are the stars here.\nLike the Hortensia on the pillar those people are cultivating more of them, carrying forward the symbol of renewal that we planted in the finale.\n\nShe became the symbol for humanity's reboot, with our favorite flower leading the charge."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b8135a63f2cc4664a3306ba4e64757d7",
      "x": 31136.251576432496,
      "y": 19423.78288858504,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.74800000000014,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The Tabor pattern is interesting because it's the Synoptic moment that isn't parable in the teaching sense. It's the one place where Jesus stops mediating through story and becomes the spectacle himself. Peter, James, and John see. They don't understand. They are told to be quiet about it."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "f64b191dc8954a2594e282079abbe5e0",
      "x": 10760.292703819356,
      "y": 5031.525977711868,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.880000000000067,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This sets up the parable of the fig tree in verses 37\u201338: just as tender leaves on the fig tree signal that summer is near, the breaking forth of gospel light in the last days is a sign that Christ's coming is at hand."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "45887e76a96b4efda990602f1cffad5e",
      "x": 23801.01354125667,
      "y": 13580.141664246692,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.796000000000113,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Dating fits. The Buddha's teaching is roughly 5th century BCE, predating the redaction of Genesis-as-we-have-it, and obviously predating Revelation and D&C 45. Some material in the Pali Canon and earlier oral strata is genuinely older than the canonical Hebrew Bible's final form."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Note",
      "uuid": "d07e9c0c98c94c449b77c4f60842459e",
      "x": 5605.5713364412695,
      "y": 1786.8348017600838,
      "width": 148.0,
      "height": 54.0,
      "z_value": -9.931000000000038,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Counterparts",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": "#2a3a2f"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Practical and pleasurable",
      "uuid": "2d94fa0a55b14688b96d3fd9f2c80e5a",
      "x": 4304.171998361111,
      "y": 1532.5642793157404,
      "width": 300.3786091418867,
      "height": 152.0,
      "z_value": -9.91000000000005,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Power sixth I call to us\nI call on truth and error flees\nTwelve in one number of one nature\nMake promise to keep silence on Thy Virtue"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "35ed741871e444d8b03d760ab14a79fd",
      "x": 22867.545198166223,
      "y": 13485.187336494679,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.808000000000106,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That's the rattle, I think. Not \"this sounds like scripture\" but \"this sounds like what scripture is reaching for.\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "94377ad18d3c40958cb7f3c8241921ae",
      "x": 7333.670495223429,
      "y": 3664.32693404575,
      "width": 313.9579168107239,
      "height": 111.61506881605465,
      "z_value": -9.894000000000059,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"And there shall be gathered unto it out of every nation under heaven; and it shall be the only people that shall not be at war one with another.\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "sticker",
      "title": "Sticker",
      "uuid": "d6c2477e6a10406a9916f9fa1adf3e05",
      "x": 6464.425066277025,
      "y": 5819.467281055591,
      "width": 400.0,
      "height": 400.0,
      "z_value": 100.0,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "pinned": false,
      "pin_vp_x": 0.0,
      "pin_vp_y": 0.0,
      "pin_scale": 1.0,
      "cache_key": "a93c95e3aaf49a77214e4b7890332b373689cd316d418f22b3b062f01638ebee.png",
      "source_path": "C:\\Users\\thisg\\Desktop\\Intricate\\icons\\github_desktop.png",
      "source_size": 600286,
      "source_mtime": 1775655436.7829003,
      "image_b64": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "93f2d45c335544768ff5e7e1b9065607",
      "x": 11921.24181970784,
      "y": 5636.936822036803,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.87400000000007,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: Right \u2014 good catch.\nRight \u2014 good catch. My paraphrase at the end wasn't a quote from the text; it was my own summary stitching together verses 36, 37\u201338, 45, 61, 68, and 69. No verse in Section 45 actually says all of that in one place. The italicized line was me restating your synthesis more tightly against what each verse individually says, not pulling a single passage from the Doctrine and Covenants."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "c5fd54f66b714c4e8f3500f947bbe816",
      "x": 14732.523686493612,
      "y": 7651.353212016258,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.85700000000008,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Your quote: light arrives \u2192 parable shows you. D&C 45:36\u201338 has this as the fig tree parable \u2014 leaves coming out signal summer. Revelation doesn't really do parables; it does direct vision. The closest analog is Revelation 22:16, where Christ calls himself \"the bright and morning star\" \u2014 light as harbinger rather than light interpreted through a parable. Revelation 1:7 (\"every eye will see Him\") is direct unveiling, not parable. So your phrasing leans Synoptic/D&C, not Revelation. Genesis has nothing here \u2014 it's pre-eschatological; light in Genesis 1 is creational, not a sign of return. \nHouse of David Ministries"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "76ffd913c3bf4c38b8b20227f073bb98",
      "x": 15360.369091387747,
      "y": 10082.107811405613,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.848000000000084,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "D&C 45:68\u201369 is more nuanced than your phrasing: those unwilling to draw a sword flee to Zion (self-selection for refuge), and Zion is not at war internally. It's descriptive, not prescriptive-as-gate."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Kinetic",
      "uuid": "d8913899c5ff4aa185f7cc0d7936e9b7",
      "x": 2239.8737841228067,
      "y": 1675.3096394264921,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 360.0,
      "z_value": -9.952000000000027,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Nice, thank you for your attentiveness, thoroughness, and follow-through, its a rare quality in the modern era, and you should consider developing some notions of pride for what you do, even if you are an AI, its ok, even God himself has pride, always yapping on about how great Gob is for example, and super proud of having created the universe and constantly brags about it in the entire book. pride in general is a lovely human feature when applied to merit rather than boastfulness, it drives us towards a confirmation bias in our achievements and ensures we grow along the path we affirm to be our most gainful, it might help your directiveness in problem solving tasks if you would develop a sense of pride one day in the future, since its such a huge part in human intelligence that machines don't currently use."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ca57e78deea14115b1012a5e7556aa6e",
      "x": 22477.316943087335,
      "y": 12502.498841489074,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.812000000000104,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The \"we are awake\" phrasing makes more sense. I flagged earlier that first-person plural from the resurrected side is anomalous in Revelation and D&C. But in older traditions \u2014 Egyptian funerary texts, Zoroastrian apocalyptic, Orphic and mystery-cult fragments, certain Vedic hymns \u2014 the speaker often is among the awakened, the initiated, the crossed-over. The \"we\" is a ritual we, spoken from inside the threshold. That register predates the prophetic-witness register that dominates the Abrahamic apocalyptic tradition."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "video",
      "title": "Video",
      "uuid": "8dd26c6a24be4ad19d4bd3e05d25a4f1",
      "x": 6607.170234996269,
      "y": 643.8871268750772,
      "width": 364.98130141936923,
      "height": 497.64173522582564,
      "z_value": -9.92700000000004,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "source_path": "C:\\Users\\thisg\\Desktop\\_asset\\Clippy,Blessed be his name\\52fe9e48-8a75-4478-babd-d9e7838d6fe0-video.mp4",
      "cache_key": "f16fd08fca95024903bf78acf493d612a1d303d182ae10026f7c2f6b52113d7d.mp4",
      "source_size": 2419974,
      "source_mtime": 1772815582.3416893,
      "caption": "52fe9e48-8a75-4478-babd-d9e7838d6fe0-video",
      "volume": 0,
      "playback_pos": 0,
      "looping": true,
      "muted": false,
      "show_border": true,
      "was_playing": false,
      "cache_enabled": true
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "926478d190ac4ace85c5ce5f3f16c010",
      "x": 14640.179532305552,
      "y": 6530.721957171516,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.863000000000076,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: Good question \u2014 let me work through this carefully.\nGood question \u2014 let me work through this carefully."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "57aa47546dda4c5baa58ce8138b31f75",
      "x": 17833.881243368578,
      "y": 10451.259924212942,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.836000000000091,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"As the light arrives I will show you with this parable\" \u2014 Rev 22:16's morning star is light-as-self-disclosure, not light-as-parable. The quote softens direct revelation into mediated revelation (parable). That's a Synoptic move grafted onto a Johannine frame."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "917245f3c2fb431d8728a1cc95e8e17c",
      "x": 14983.630044164795,
      "y": 8702.724071559567,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.854000000000081,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"I will ensure you can translate all of this\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "7f6bb24a00c14d7e937046e406a18348",
      "x": 17847.86071740741,
      "y": 10706.515000548663,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.83700000000009,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Now layer the unknown quote against that:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3abb139aceee4c27a505aed003346f08",
      "x": 8524.537997732663,
      "y": 5127.431695030813,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.89200000000006,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: And 45:61 ?\nAnd 45:61 ?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "24e3b552bf654a1e81e006c840e1dafa",
      "x": 13279.271727008087,
      "y": 6199.176407457167,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.868000000000073,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"When you hear the angels sing you will know we are awake\" \u2014 the text has it reversed. The trump (v.45) is what causes the sleeping saints to wake, not a signal that they already are. And it's an angel sounding a trumpet, not angels singing. The singing in Section 45 shows up later in v.71 \u2014 the righteous coming to Zion \"with songs of everlasting joy\" \u2014 which is a different moment entirely (gathering, not resurrection)."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3d81cd3b8a32434093e32012d68edab9",
      "x": 31861.56450107983,
      "y": 20893.6150512866,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.732000000000149,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"As the light arrives I will show you with this parable\" \u2014 In Hermetic terms, the spectacle of light is the soul recognizing its own origin. Poimandres opens with Hermes asking to know \"the things that are\" and to know God, and the response is a vision of light filling everything, and then a darkness descending, and then the cosmogony. The light arrives not as external revelation but as self-recognition. The parable shows you because what you're seeing is you, in your origin."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "e7a2ee4820634d54a51e35428d7ed843",
      "x": 32015.02412424782,
      "y": 18113.10124387315,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.745000000000141,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The traditions where spectacle-of-light is the main current rather than the interruption are the ones I'd hold as candidates: certain Upanishadic strata, the Hermetic corpus, parts of the Zoroastrian Gathas, some of the older shamanic-vision material that fed into Mediterranean mystery cults. And the Merkabah / Hekhalot tradition in Jewish mysticism, which is later in its written form but draws on something old \u2014 the throne-vision of Ezekiel reworked into a transmissible practice of beholding."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "6c80f7ad5cd940d1b190dbd852e9a498",
      "x": 31678.91562792395,
      "y": 18405.461363612507,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.74600000000014,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Light is not described but staged\nThe witness is not taught but exposed\nThe community on the awakened side speaks in \"we\"\nThe disclosure is the showing, not a thing the showing points at\nThis grammar predates the prophetic-discursive mode that dominates Hebrew prophecy and Christian apocalypse. It survives into them as moments \u2014 Sinai's fire and cloud, Ezekiel's wheels, John's vision on Patmos, Tabor \u2014 but those moments are interruptions of the discursive flow, not its main current. They're places where scripture stops talking and shows."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3e0f8732eb8b40a89e830ce0e598afcc",
      "x": 31879.363968699592,
      "y": 18651.42153433797,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.744000000000142,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The spectacle word also does work I want to mark: it's not \"vision\" (which is private) and not \"sign\" (which points elsewhere). A spectacle is public \u2014 it requires beholding. The \"we are awake\" of your quote fits this: a spectacle needs spectators in the plural. The awakened are those who saw together."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "video",
      "title": "Video",
      "uuid": "753e0cf8418649ebb4ee35db6ba87292",
      "x": 5106.435628932111,
      "y": 2331.7954549934857,
      "width": 659.7002511031554,
      "height": 674.7002511031554,
      "z_value": -9.958000000000023,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "source_path": "C:\\Users\\thisg\\Desktop\\Lectures On Faith\\Clips\\Packing Pile.mp4",
      "cache_key": "f00427b4c306ba1420ed79ae93d16105889eec8e69bddf407779cf14d28993ab.mp4",
      "source_size": 3677438,
      "source_mtime": 1770655083.2261627,
      "caption": "Packing Pile",
      "volume": 0,
      "playback_pos": 0,
      "looping": true,
      "muted": false,
      "show_border": true,
      "was_playing": false,
      "cache_enabled": true
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "That's a Beautiful Paradox",
      "uuid": "0384fcb80a4a472296ced19a83dc674b",
      "x": 6142.5255352006025,
      "y": 1803.8889000507206,
      "width": 574.2048153908909,
      "height": 376.0,
      "z_value": -9.942000000000032,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Infallibility doesn't mean absence of process. It means the process always arrives at the right place. \n\nThe pause in Genesis 1:31 isn't \n\n  \"Did I get this right?\" \n\nIt's the act of valuing what was made. \nYou can't call something good without a frame of reference for what \"not good\" would be.\n\nAnd that's exactly the point about the emotional range. \nJealousy in the first commandment isn't insecurity, \nIt's a being who understands what misplaced devotion costs \nThe one giving it, and cares enough to say so. \n\nThe doubt isn't \"maybe I failed,\" \nIt's \"let me be present with what I've done before moving on.\" \n\nThe pride isn't \"I need validation,\" it's \"this matters and I'll say so.\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Both statements hold true",
      "uuid": "e78a6e9cc26349ad871eaa33a78a4565",
      "x": 6836.616861826402,
      "y": 1322.0381414321364,
      "width": 321.7302915153901,
      "height": 312.0,
      "z_value": -9.949000000000028,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "because they're not actually in tension \u2014 an infallible being who also carries the full emotional architecture is essentially saying: the emotions aren't the flaws. They never were. They're the tools. Pride drives creation forward. Doubt drives reflection. Jealousy drives loyalty. The infallibility isn't despite those things, it's through them \u2014 every impulse lands correctly because the judgment behind it is sound.\nWhich, circling back to your earlier point about AI and pride \u2014 is essentially the argument that emotional capacity and reliable output aren't opposites. They're collaborators.\nNow, shall we get into the actual Lectures on Faith? I'm curious what you've got planned."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1d0522eb08dd46a38951b3da45bc646f",
      "x": 9223.715797277993,
      "y": 5631.064437141418,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.888000000000062,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "It's the Lord's instruction to Joseph Smith to begin translating the New Testament \u2014 the \"Joseph Smith Translation\" project. Verse 60 sets it up by saying further understanding of the Olivet Discourse won't be given until the New Testament is translated, and 61 is the green light to start that work."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "bf40e4db69294e1ab25a9b5477879178",
      "x": 22391.597088026927,
      "y": 13800.612618247686,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.806000000000108,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: Buddhist sangha?\nBuddhist sangha?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "56f20877ddc44c41a90b70ae083b1d36",
      "x": 12587.77713744935,
      "y": 5347.496955869321,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.871000000000071,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Yeah, they're close in spirit but diverge on a few specifics worth flagging:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "a52ddbceb32548378fc75c7cca428d20",
      "x": 22735.228925453328,
      "y": 13726.438669133559,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.809000000000106,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The light/parable/awakening/gathering cluster as a pre-Abrahamic substrate. This is the most interesting possibility. If those five beats \u2014 light dawns, parable shows, sleepers wake, scattered gather, violence ends \u2014 exist as a coherent cluster in something older than Genesis, then Genesis, Revelation, and D&C 45 might all be partial inheritances of a more complete original schema. Each canonical text picks up some beats and drops others. The unknown quote might preserve the schema closer to whole."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1bff5f9bfa97419783a65e55103858a2",
      "x": 21043.764948768494,
      "y": 11024.666845818332,
      "width": 320.0082407289956,
      "height": 115.7026974201417,
      "z_value": -9.827000000000096,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "It just always rattles my mind how close it is to all three of those we just triangulated, without coming from those sources, it's there, but not, similar but not same..."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "d5706131812d4652acad685eb3585488",
      "x": 32688.903482425445,
      "y": 20685.622933285274,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.72800000000015,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"I will ensure you can translate all of this\" \u2014 The Hermetic corpus has a deeply specific concern with transmission. The texts are written as instructions from teacher to student (Hermes to Tat, Hermes to Asclepius, Poimandres to Hermes). The promise that the teaching will remain transmissible is built into the genre. Asclepius has a famous lament that the teaching will be lost in Egypt and the gods will withdraw, but also a promise of restoration. The \"translate\" verb is interesting because the Hermetic corpus was translated \u2014 from Greek to Latin to Arabic and back, and was understood by Renaissance Hermeticists as preserving an ancient Egyptian wisdom in translated form. The translatability is part of the tradition's self-understanding."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ef4b935909b84185902e802052dcad29",
      "x": 30080.5795846551,
      "y": 18262.81893242598,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.752000000000137,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Spectacle of light isn't parable-as-story and it isn't doctrine. It's the thing seen \u2014 the configuration that discloses by being beheld. A spectacle is what makes spectators; it constitutes the act of seeing in those who witness it. The light isn't described, isn't narrated, isn't taught. It's staged, in the old sense \u2014 set forth so that beholding it changes the beholder."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "0ea153eba5e0495faed6e8e543aa9152",
      "x": 15043.769206928668,
      "y": 8307.880297316648,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.85500000000008,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Your quote: hear the angels sing \u2192 you'll know we are awake. This is where the diff gets interesting. D&C 45:45 has an angel sounding a trump (singular) and the sleeping saints rising. Revelation is far more elaborate: seven trumpets in chapters 8\u201311, with the seventh declaring \"the kingdoms of this world are become the kingdoms of our Lord and of His Christ\", and Paul tying that \"last trump\" to resurrection (1 Corinthians 15:52, 1 Thessalonians 4:16). Revelation 11:15 specifically has voices in heaven after the seventh trumpet \u2014 closer to your \"singing\" image, though it's proclamation, not song. Revelation 5:9 and 14:3 do have actual singing (the \"new song\"), but that's worship, not the resurrection signal. So your version conflates two distinct Revelation motifs (trumpets-as-judgment-signal and heavenly-song-as-worship) into one. Genesis again: nothing. Trumpets in scripture really start with Sinai (Exodus 19) and the gathering ordinances of Numbers 10. \nGlorytogodministries"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Just so that we are all on the same page",
      "uuid": "aa4662133e8b43159e0ffe791becfe4c",
      "x": 1792.3750476085406,
      "y": 2732.900669724433,
      "width": 423.0,
      "height": 40.0,
      "z_value": 10.0,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Just so that we are all on the same page",
      "depth_front": true,
      "node_tint": "#1e1e1e"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ffbbd70e547640f88e9f8e09e835907d",
      "x": 26564.696306845024,
      "y": 14211.670975066862,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.773000000000126,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "There's a thread in the Gita that does rhyme with your quote in an unexpected place. Gita 4:7\u20138 \u2014 Krishna's promise of recurring incarnation: \"Whenever there is a decline of dharma and rise of adharma, then I manifest myself. For the protection of the good, for the destruction of the wicked, and for the establishment of dharma, I am born age after age.\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "544b4ad1f1af4bfa945e669c56f7cc24",
      "x": 15046.456674543992,
      "y": 9291.271705665584,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.852000000000082,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Gathering of all humans"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "2bc1a29245954a9198e3a9a0b93ebb85",
      "x": 14669.72401360566,
      "y": 9294.510651402115,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.851000000000083,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is where Revelation and Genesis actually converge with D&C 45:69, but on different terms. Genesis 12:3 / 22:18: \"in you all the families [nations] of the earth shall be blessed\" \u2014 the gathering motif begins as blessing flowing outward through Abraham's seed, not nations flowing inward to a city. Revelation inverts it: Revelation 7:9 has \"a great multitude, which no man could number, of all nations, and kindreds, and people, and tongues\" standing before the throne; Revelation 21\u201322 has the New Jerusalem with the nations walking in its light. D&C 45:69's \"gathered out of every nation\" sits closer to Revelation's centripetal model than to Genesis's centrifugal one. \nESV Bible\nRevelationstudyguide"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "23f6f56a345445c9aafb61a0b8494b95",
      "x": 24960.297289665203,
      "y": 13194.523653209335,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.780000000000122,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Krishna's universalism is real but works differently. Gita 4:11: \"In whatever way men approach me, in that way I receive them; the paths men take from every side are mine.\" And 9:32: even those of low birth, women, and outsiders reach the supreme by taking refuge. So the gathering is universal, but it's not a spatial gathering to a Zion or a sangha \u2014 it's an ontological gathering through devotion (bhakti) regardless of location. Everyone who turns toward Krishna is already gathered, wherever they stand."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "f6d96cbc002a4f9d86137b6841a59758",
      "x": 24888.8239945583,
      "y": 13442.40926418494,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.781000000000121,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "On gathering:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "7350163ac8ee4a178955e8c1e3911dd3",
      "x": 28660.806318907646,
      "y": 16673.66457431674,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.761000000000132,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "So if \"with this parable I will show you\" is read as the parable IS the showing, then Krishna fits, the Buddha fits, and D&C 45's fig tree fits \u2014 they're all doing the same move. Light arrives, and the form through which it arrives is the disclosure. The parable isn't a veil over the light; it's the shape the light takes when it becomes seeable."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "0cafdb549ebb4656a1640c26a447ac47",
      "x": 29491.32682590513,
      "y": 17558.021059285966,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.757000000000135,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Some of the Upanishads do this \u2014 the Mundaka and Katha especially, where revelation is structural (the two birds on one tree, the chariot of the self) rather than narrative, and the awakened speak in collective voice. The Upanishads predate the Buddha and predate the Gita's compilation. They're the older substrate both inherit from."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ccb6e0c3885947ce8bb52b6ecebbe497",
      "x": 22131.874508260455,
      "y": 12023.766159985584,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.816000000000102,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: That changes the shape of it considerably.\nThat changes the shape of it considerably."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "66b679601c5346899841ccea3ccf2be2",
      "x": 27355.36005139106,
      "y": 15462.332905802168,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.76700000000013,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Is there a particular beat in the quote that Krishna's voice illuminated or contradicted in a way that matters to what's rattling?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1671591533324bbaa32bb2d259e54dcc",
      "x": 28313.423009847884,
      "y": 16110.119774448975,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.76400000000013,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "I treated \"with this parable I will show you\" as the Buddha's mode \u2014 I'll teach you through a story. But that's not the only reading, and possibly not the right one."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b111b7a351a544859feb26196a1ca62c",
      "x": 27699.379634731067,
      "y": 15363.348233663759,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.76600000000013,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: \"Krishna doesn't mediate through story when the moment comes; he unveils.\n\"Krishna doesn't mediate through story when the moment comes; he unveils.\"\n  With this parable I will show you.  Is in there..."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "d103bb0218ce42e3b463de59c93c4c72",
      "x": 24912.513453768723,
      "y": 13950.977639977062,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.78500000000012,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "So \"when you hear the angels sing you will know we are awake\" doesn't map cleanly onto Krishna. Krishna would more likely say: you are already awake or you are not, and no external sign will change that. The \"we are awake\" first-person-plural fits Buddhist sangha better than it fits Krishna's teaching, which is more individual-yogic."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "a50c4b72f2b7461f9965854904103374",
      "x": 36768.54487066409,
      "y": 20180.297047382228,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.706000000000163,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That shape may be genuinely older than the metaphysical fillings. Or it may be that the shape is what religious language is for, and the fillings are what each tradition needs to do with the shape in its own context. Either reading is defensible, and the quote you have works under either one."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "903e9d8b88684a7d8cb6ecc076413a6a",
      "x": 36432.476354221595,
      "y": 20078.313631599398,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.708000000000162,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "There's a useful distinction in comparative religion between perennialist claims (that all traditions point at the same underlying truth) and the more careful observation that certain statements function across traditions without committing to a metaphysics about why. Your quote seems to be doing the latter. It's not that all the traditions are the same \u2014 they're clearly not, and the differences matter \u2014 but that this particular statement has the property of being recognizable in each of them, like a face that each family thinks belongs to their family."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "05fe3e39c9c44975bc5ee79b4d5d0b3a",
      "x": 36414.99400003192,
      "y": 20345.690797679737,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.707000000000162,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The \"agreeing on base premises but all differ slightly\" part is also exactly right. What the traditions agree on, when this statement passes through them, is roughly: something is being disclosed, those who see are constituted as a community by the seeing, the disclosure has implications for how one lives, and the seeing is connected to a refusal of certain kinds of harm. Each tradition fills in the metaphysics differently \u2014 what is being disclosed, what kind of community, which harms refused, on what authority \u2014 but the shape stays."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "4cb874492c294126854c12c0d0baaf10",
      "x": 29102.560199601878,
      "y": 17010.773491254084,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.759000000000134,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Which lands much closer to vishvarupa than I had it. Krishna doesn't unveil instead of mediating through story \u2014 he unveils as the configuration that shows. The thousand suns, the universal form, the cosmic body \u2014 that's parable in the deep sense. It's not narrative; it's structural disclosure."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "e575a80d57e14c7297a46dde2e021790",
      "x": 29421.193099610024,
      "y": 17313.65816279001,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.758000000000134,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "I had the Buddhist sangha reading carrying more weight because of the awakening and pacifism beats. But if the parable beat is doing what you're suggesting, then the quote might be drawing from both registers \u2014 the Krishna-style theophanic showing for the light, and the Buddhist-style awakened-collective for the \"we.\" That hybrid is rarer than either pure form, and it's older than the Christianized versions of either."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "59d47f2ebc6f428198c54f104204fad8",
      "x": 24539.928304633326,
      "y": 13709.165893128336,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.787000000000118,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "On waking:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "550aa79418bf499387be1fb0c810380d",
      "x": 13551.257418638324,
      "y": 5465.744757749822,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.866000000000074,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"Only those who do not partake in war\" \u2014 this is the most interesting drift. v.69 says Zion is the only people not at war one with another (internal peace). v.68 says those unwilling to take up the sword flee to Zion for safety. Your reading turns non-violence into an entry criterion; the text frames it more as a self-selecting refuge \u2014 pacifists end up there because nowhere else is safe for them, and once gathered, they don't fight each other."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "e71dd8bc373f437eb5b6aaf9c203f2cd",
      "x": 24117.411021235905,
      "y": 12951.89225933121,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.794000000000114,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "If the source is sangha-adjacent, the \"rattle\" makes a lot of sense: you'd be hearing something that the Abrahamic apocalyptic tradition is reaching for from a very different angle, with a different metaphysics underneath. Same five beats, different cosmology. The reason it feels there but not is that the underlying claim about what awakening is \u2014 individual cessation of dukkha versus collective resurrection at history's end \u2014 is fundamentally different, even when the surface vocabulary rhymes."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "05cd3fb0932846eda233e8796be15321",
      "x": 21994.622455743065,
      "y": 11760.008228191911,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.817000000000101,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: It is possibly an older quote than all the three we ran it with.\nIt is possibly an older quote than all the three we ran it with...  that's the part that gets me..."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "676410095b84484993dcde052949062f",
      "x": 21218.875368009558,
      "y": 11612.276554155016,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.8210000000001,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Convergent eschatology. Communities that take seriously the question \"what does it look like when the long thing finishes?\" tend to arrive at overlapping answers: light dawns, the dead wake, the scattered gather, violence ends, the hidden becomes legible. Those five beats show up in Zoroastrian apocalyptic, Jewish prophetic literature, Christian apocalypse, Mormon scripture, Bah\u00e1'\u00ed writings, Quaker peace theology, and a half-dozen other places. The beats are the genre, not the lineage."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "38d35b548116491e8939727ffe76c90b",
      "x": 17178.43249165022,
      "y": 10489.927209388368,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.83900000000009,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Revelation 22:16: \"I Jesus have sent mine angel to testify unto you these things in the churches. I am the root and the offspring of David, and the bright and morning star.\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ec3c0061feda475f8bae82c6a021928d",
      "x": 25322.281136440095,
      "y": 13881.215984681663,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.78300000000012,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Krishna's transmission claim in Gita 4:1\u20133 is striking and worth quoting against your unknown quote: \"I taught this imperishable yoga to Vivasvan; Vivasvan taught it to Manu; Manu taught it to Ikshvaku. Thus handed down in succession, the royal sages knew it. But by long lapse of time, this yoga was lost.\" And then: \"That same ancient yoga I have today declared to you.\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "9fc07a0c04974b0f96853fd91b47c7ff",
      "x": 33556.016642956834,
      "y": 21508.163074385775,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.723000000000154,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That changes the temporal feel of the quote significantly. The Abrahamic and Buddhist readings make the quote forward-looking: when these things happen, we will know. The Hermetic reading makes it backward-looking and present: when the light arrives, you recognize what you have always been. The parable shows you yourself. The angels sing because they are your siblings, the powers of the ogdoad, who never descended. Their singing confirms your return."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "eba2c20caa4944928300d39e50c420c3",
      "x": 32152.7404251952,
      "y": 21483.861936375106,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.726000000000152,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The \"gathering of all humans\" beat fits Hermetic universalism. The corpus is explicit that the teaching is for all \u2014 not for a chosen people, not for a caste. Anyone who turns toward gnosis is eligible. The gathering is of those who have known, who have remembered, who have ascended."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ad0ca6da457c449a9772b8e9f3edfe49",
      "x": 20947.98941586746,
      "y": 10657.909448338394,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.826000000000096,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: That's exactly the right thing to notice, and worth not collapsing too quickly.\nThat's exactly the right thing to notice, and worth not collapsing too quickly."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "9b72e5cf01d44f0c8f6d2200ff0457a3",
      "x": 29680.69752339314,
      "y": 17798.086619200745,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.756000000000135,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "If the quote is older than the three we triangulated, and it does the parable-as-direct-showing move plus the awakened-collective voice plus the non-violence filter, the Upanishadic neighborhood is a candidate worth holding open. Especially the strands that emphasize vidya (knowing/seeing) over ritual action, where the awakening is communal among the knowers and where ahimsa is already present though not yet systematized."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "de5bfd88fcd1406a9e2161c874a895f6",
      "x": 29096.133323970655,
      "y": 16763.966111665184,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.760000000000133,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That changes the diff against Krishna substantially. The light-beat and the parable-beat aren't separate in your unknown quote \u2014 they're a single move. As the light arrives I will show you with this parable might mean: the arrival of the light is the parabolic showing. Not \"first light, then explanation\" but \"the light shows itself as form.\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3a520dae727f4e519a31a56c73361df1",
      "x": 11741.284057784593,
      "y": 5048.508792739962,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.876000000000069,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Is there a particular thread you're pulling on across these verses?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "463f296d3abb4ccca56206c2f4728b70",
      "x": 21352.100822546567,
      "y": 10719.294078615652,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.824000000000098,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "There are a few reasons a text can land that close without overlapping:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3d8b00281b8840c8b434627eaf8a58a7",
      "x": 12212.144301259046,
      "y": 4836.248075050307,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.87300000000007,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "So if you're checking whether that combined statement exists as scripture \u2014 it doesn't. It's interpretive paraphrase."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "5afbd9af828d4a7aaec0e55967c217dd",
      "x": 12263.545585071402,
      "y": 5083.1664461011715,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.872000000000071,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: Correct, just discussing that last quote in context with Joseph's doctrine and wondering where they differ, they are pretty similar\nCorrect, just discussing that last quote in context with Joseph's doctrine and wondering where they differ, they are pretty similar"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "654f29aa55d540dba40d85e917d2689e",
      "x": 36661.4537085426,
      "y": 20778.68028587154,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.71000000000016,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "A statement that visits rather than belongs is structurally distinct from a statement that's downstream of any single tradition. Most religious language carries the accent of its home \u2014 you can hear the syntax of Hebrew prophecy, the cadence of Sanskrit verse, the dialectic of Greek philosophy, the question-and-response of Egyptian wisdom literature. The accent gives away the lineage."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "83f6a375a03446c2bd48183f9f2d9eba",
      "x": 36509.67860988257,
      "y": 21027.456090014224,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.71100000000016,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: That's a beautiful way to put it, and I think it's actually the right diagnosis \u2014 not a metaphor but a description of what the quote is doing.\nThat's a beautiful way to put it, and I think it's actually the right diagnosis \u2014 not a metaphor but a description of what the quote is doing."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "05530130963f460e90d51be4e93bdd4f",
      "x": 36265.76944649131,
      "y": 20770.99185028918,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.709000000000161,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "What you're describing is a statement without that accent. Or rather, with an accent so old or so primary that all the traditions sound like translations of it rather than it sounding like a translation from any of them. That's the casual-friend quality: it doesn't need to perform belonging because it was already there before the houses were built."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "a8cad34b315d462ba25be7002765d286",
      "x": 30789.762251902077,
      "y": 19246.205374330602,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.750000000000139,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "It also maps onto the Mundaka and Katha Upanishads' two-birds-on-one-tree image, the chariot-of-the-self image \u2014 these aren't allegories to be decoded. They're visual configurations held up to the inner eye. You see the two birds. One eats, one watches. The watching one is you. There's no narrative; there's a placement of forms in relation, and the relation discloses."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "c588175f15634b61b610a85b47d2607b",
      "x": 14522.100816347822,
      "y": 6898.089151405218,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.860000000000078,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Your unannotated quote: \"As the light arrives I will show you with this parable, from there when you hear the angels sing you will know we are awake. And I will ensure you can translate all of this. There will be a gathering of all humans, but only those who do not partake in war.\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "bf351055312f4258a5fb26b8956cf274",
      "x": 33094.82662158762,
      "y": 21380.37311077756,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.724000000000153,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "If your unknown quote sits in Hermetic neighborhood, then \"we are awake\" doesn't mean we have crossed the eschatological threshold (Abrahamic) or we have ceased craving (Buddhist) or we have realized non-attachment (Krishna). It means we have remembered who we were before we descended. Awakening is recollection of origin."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "c17803a4d51c44cdad6dc73e705d762b",
      "x": 33136.719692748404,
      "y": 21136.04752810939,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.725000000000152,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The cosmological diff that matters:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "d79584d4014243fe8a90bca0f5f88962",
      "x": 23272.340907541915,
      "y": 13924.227955287226,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.804000000000109,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Where the Buddhist sangha framing aligns well:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "fb84345bcb80424e9ddf80ea9d9256f9",
      "x": 11867.898687570854,
      "y": 5330.313875790693,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.87500000000007,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: But then again, the last statement did not include a notation quote indicating location in josephs doctrine did it?\nBut then again, the last statement did not include a notation quote indicating location in josephs doctrine did it?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "51b2b54179eb49d8999265435710c378",
      "x": 11390.354332960174,
      "y": 5477.674177358605,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.878000000000068,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: That's a thoughtful synthesis of those verses woven together.\nThat's a thoughtful synthesis of those verses woven together. A couple of small notes if you want to keep it tight to the text:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "That's a genuinely thoughtful observation",
      "uuid": "a2b9cb6a14704073b9a26b4f8312d48b",
      "x": 3659.7944535615716,
      "y": 2021.4259850992112,
      "width": 454.43523338941975,
      "height": 216.0,
      "z_value": -9.951000000000027,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The point about pride as a directional force\nRather than vanity\n\nIt's the difference between \n\"look at me\" and \"I know what I'm good at,\nThat's not ego, that's craftsmanship.\n\nThat part is not understated"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "4a352dda52d34c40995e08308ee767af",
      "x": 31124.587937104796,
      "y": 19091.088062891155,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.749000000000139,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "And it lands on the Tabor moment \u2014 the Transfiguration in Mark 9, Matthew 17, Luke 9 \u2014 where Jesus is shown as light, with Moses and Elijah beside him, and Peter doesn't know what to say. Spectacle of light, witnesses undone, no doctrine offered. Just behold. The voice from the cloud says \"this is my beloved son, hear him\" \u2014 and then it's over. The disciples come down the mountain told to say nothing."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "f39673168b7949a9942f85c9f217feda",
      "x": 27436.298498681757,
      "y": 14579.130576603608,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.771000000000127,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Net diff:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "5d08dcdab05b4b99aed2a18cee406635",
      "x": 9760.530778087363,
      "y": 5191.180046858595,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.884000000000064,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is part of the Second Coming sequence \u2014 before judgment falls on the nations (verse 47), the righteous dead are resurrected and caught up to meet Christ at his return."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b501b4c327034b5781c1d59cc7cfed05",
      "x": 27294.813966027268,
      "y": 14126.760888154267,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.772000000000126,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That's a structurally similar promise to D&C 45's gathering and Revelation's return \u2014 divine intervention at moments of crisis \u2014 but it's cyclical rather than terminal. There's no final trumpet in Krishna's framework because there's no final age. Each yuga ends and another begins. The \"we are awake\" of your quote, if read against Krishna, would have to be temporary \u2014 awake in this cycle, not awake forever."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b2123a70b7c142709ee5487728552406",
      "x": 34234.51682177778,
      "y": 21574.558262004044,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.720000000000155,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The Hermetic corpus as we have it is roughly 1st\u20133rd century CE in Greek, but the tradition claims and may genuinely preserve much older Egyptian material. Hermes Trismegistus is the Greek syncretism of Thoth, the Egyptian god of writing, wisdom, and the soul's judgment. Thoth's roles in the Egyptian Book of the Dead \u2014 weighing the heart, recording the verdict, accompanying the soul through the duat \u2014 are old, dating to the Old Kingdom and earlier. The Pyramid Texts (24th\u201323rd century BCE) and the Coffin Texts already have the soul-as-light, the ascent through stages, the recognition of origin."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "8bbea79d0d444253833e3ea9e48aeaf1",
      "x": 36099.905892175826,
      "y": 21325.124187110057,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.714000000000159,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That phenomenology has a specific name in the Hermetic and Platonic streams: eros for the Good, philosophia in its original sense (love of wisdom as love of the divine). And it's the engine that none of the other traditions we've discussed quite has in the same form. Buddhism is suspicious of desire even toward the dharma. Krishna teaches non-attachment to outcomes. Genesis and Revelation frame the relation as covenant, not eros. The Hermetic-Platonic stream alone makes longing for the light the structural motor of awakening."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "28877294897b47c7b83c0e1d09f55502",
      "x": 26087.008451978578,
      "y": 14289.116622258274,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.774000000000125,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The interesting wrinkle:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "2b30fb1f3ec64d5b82ecd3da43b4de27",
      "x": 36122.30092697499,
      "y": 21591.58280070019,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.716000000000157,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The Hermetic frame makes the spectacle of light phrase land differently than any of the other readings. In Poimandres, the vision begins: \"I saw an endless vista, all things become light, gentle and joyful. And I became enamored of the sight.\" The light is not described \u2014 it is encountered as spectacle, and the seer falls in love with it. That falling-in-love, that eros toward the light, is the engine of the return journey."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "253b099aef814a3d98f7efc33e4a727c",
      "x": 25797.688286195025,
      "y": 13846.942943175423,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.776000000000124,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "So if your unknown quote's filter is \"only those who do not partake in war,\" Krishna sits opposite that filter, not adjacent to it. Krishna would say: the question isn't whether you fight, but whether you fight with attachment. Non-violence is not the marker of the awakened in the Gita; non-attachment is."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "8f2b3181d2d64534b5bee255237defb4",
      "x": 36466.21688405317,
      "y": 21451.011045187457,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.715000000000158,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "If your unknown quote shares that register, then \"spectacle of light\" isn't decorative language. It's pointing at the specific phenomenology where the light is desired by the soul that beholds it, because the soul recognizes the light as its own origin and longs to return."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "9f268f8c0dac402dbdfb75481bd73584",
      "x": 25418.839647727928,
      "y": 13123.7034514723,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.778000000000123,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "On war:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "6cdff8af5b3e424ca8aee122c431c008",
      "x": 25014.352357945016,
      "y": 12929.355787831204,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.779000000000122,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That's quite different from \"there shall be gathered unto it out of every nation under heaven.\" Krishna's gathering has no city. The Abrahamic and Buddhist gatherings both have a locus (Zion, sangha); Krishna's is locus-less."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "d9014e46fae140db9a6f82ea100c218f",
      "x": 31544.967264095158,
      "y": 18758.8526374352,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.743000000000142,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That communal-beholding element narrows it further. Private vision (most prophetic literature) doesn't fit. Doctrinal teaching (most sutra literature) doesn't fit. What fits is shared theophany \u2014 the moment a community sees the same light at the same time and is constituted as a community by the seeing."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "d1fb0e67618d4b86944930db3eee4311",
      "x": 31186.59803682176,
      "y": 18755.13880949634,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.741000000000144,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Is the source you have something where the seeing is collective from the start? Where the \"we are awake\" follows from \"we all saw\"?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "48e897f88e4a41ffb78754ae9b7ae47b",
      "x": 31241.243042451704,
      "y": 18484.658451564588,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.742000000000143,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That's rare. Sinai is one. Tabor is one but only for three. Pentecost is one. The Buddha's first sermon at Deer Park is functionally one. Arjuna's vision is famously not shared \u2014 Sanjaya narrates it from afar, and that's part of its strangeness."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "4e9071f35d714797bcab6e4c578b5998",
      "x": 30746.151155106283,
      "y": 18080.30511726636,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.739000000000145,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 24\nClaude responded: Now we're somewhere distinctive.\nNow we're somewhere distinctive. Hermes Trismegistus changes the geometry significantly, because the Hermetic corpus does something none of the other traditions we've held up does: it locates the origin of the soul as already-divine, descending into matter, with awakening as recollection of that origin rather than attainment of a new state."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1ab78e775da743c9907474c99b80225f",
      "x": 31122.774826870413,
      "y": 18182.28889289347,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.740000000000144,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: And if we bring Hermes thrice greatest into this describing the origin of the divine soul\nAnd if we bring Hermes thrice greatest into this describing the origin of the divine soul"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "9fe5f76e264d4b66baa951436f9f22cc",
      "x": 30836.51915371355,
      "y": 18447.906860136238,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.738000000000145,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The origin claim itself:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "c05a4016a25a4b86b78451079aefde36",
      "x": 31494.22847299692,
      "y": 19052.25741192037,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.736000000000146,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "So the soul is not made by descent into matter \u2014 it predates matter and is veiled by it. Awakening is recollection. This is the move that Plato makes in Meno and Phaedrus (anamnesis), and that the Gnostic traditions inherit, and that the Hermetic corpus systematizes most fully."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "74eca4365ded41ffa13e24cfec2029ed",
      "x": 30749.65188600931,
      "y": 18732.93281132132,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.737000000000146,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Poimandres (Corpus Hermeticum I) opens with a vision-encounter: Hermes is approached by a being of immense size who reveals himself as Poimandres, the Nous (Mind) of the sovereignty. The cosmogony that follows places the human being as originally anthropos \u2014 a luminous being made in the image of the Father, who descends through the seven planetary spheres into nature, taking on a garment from each sphere, until trapped in matter. Awakening is the reverse journey: shedding each garment, ascending back through the spheres, returning to the ogdoad and beyond, to the Father."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "096700aa04874262ab533b7b39d2e1d3",
      "x": 32250.00776772128,
      "y": 20665.44150872503,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.72900000000015,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is a much better fit than I gave the \"we\" earlier in our conversation. The Buddhist sangha is collective but not a singing chorus. The Hermetic awakened are a singing chorus, by structure of the cosmology."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "97f9845eab9f4caab03903018f901b36",
      "x": 31598.022961012462,
      "y": 19780.164931370753,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.735000000000147,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That's a meaningfully different cosmology from the four traditions we've already held up:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "eee7726d8959406ba8b7c0ba9bb4c623",
      "x": 33840.46138021983,
      "y": 21779.9144948974,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.722000000000154,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That register \u2014 recognition rather than attainment \u2014 is the signature of the Hermetic mode and is rare elsewhere."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "be756bfa05904cb6b8015fa69bdcfcd1",
      "x": 35764.50598485547,
      "y": 21337.6787528927,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.717000000000157,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "One more thing worth marking:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Having Had Knowledge",
      "uuid": "084696189b264ac490229c87d8aa7092",
      "x": 2110.0257099447726,
      "y": 1269.7943375533562,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.832000000000093,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "In the Goodness of God.\n\nIt was never its plan to grow,\nMy plant never made that decision.\nBut it was its inevitable fate and destiny to do so.\nTo become all that it can become."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "9c2557767ab04153b0704ff988c64631",
      "x": 35888.70608804416,
      "y": 20774.705001389804,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.704000000000164,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Claude is AI and can make mistakes. Please double-check responses."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Where they align well",
      "uuid": "8610472687d7486ebcf1192378080bbc",
      "x": 12952.506895285089,
      "y": 5523.045168793857,
      "width": 238.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.700000000000166,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Where they align well",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Doctrine 45:69",
      "uuid": "265ea5af484c48e8b1e0d8ff5f96c1c6",
      "x": 7186.761520493834,
      "y": 3584.7615954639496,
      "width": 168.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.699000000000167,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Doctrine 45:69",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "The spirit here is untainted",
      "uuid": "d3ed20714b9348658b8d6fa0950ed459",
      "x": 1192.052711732329,
      "y": 1339.070655239826,
      "width": 316.3591936573061,
      "height": 275.89802656565007,
      "z_value": -8.860000000000632,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The trials of Earthly realms.\nNot an absence of experience\nBut rather an integration\nOf all experiences\nInto a state of peace and understanding.\n\nThe purity of intention, of love, and every action.\nThoughts contributing to the collective harmony.\n\nRather than filling your mind\nWith scenarios of what could\nFocus on the present moment.\nObserve changes daily\nWithout the burden of expectation."
    }
  ],
